gettyimages-1388588882.jpg?width=640&amp;height=426.66666666666663&amp;crop=640%3A426.66666666666663%2Csmart&amp;quality=75&amp;auto=webp 640w, https://assets.editorial.aetnd.com/uploads/2009/10/japanese-internment-camps-gettyimages-1388588882.jpg?width=750&amp;height=500&amp;crop=750%3A500%2Csmart&amp;quality=75&amp;auto=webp 750w, https://assets.editorial.aetnd.com/uploads/2009/10/japanese-internment-camps-gettyimages-1388588882.jpg?width=828&amp;height=552&amp;crop=828%3A552%2Csmart&amp;quality=75&amp;auto=webp 828w, https://assets.editorial.aetnd.com/uploads/2009/10/japanese-internment-camps-gettyimages-1388588882.jpg?width=1080&amp;height=540&amp;crop=1080%3A540%2Csmart&amp;quality=75&amp;auto=webp 1080w, https://assets.editorial.aetnd.com/uploads/2009/10/japanese-internment-camps-gettyimages-1388588882.jpg?width=1248&amp;height=624&amp;crop=1248%3A624%2Csmart&amp;quality=75&amp;auto=webp 1248w, https://assets.editorial.aetnd.com/uploads/2009/10/japanese-internment-camps-gettyimages-1388588882.jpg?width=1920&amp;height=960&amp;crop=1920%3A960%2Csmart&amp;quality=75&amp;auto=webp 1920w, https://assets.editorial.aetnd.com/uploads/2009/10/japanese-internment-camps-gettyimages-1388588882.jpg?width=2048&amp;height=1024&amp;crop=2048%3A1024%2Csmart&amp;quality=75&amp;auto=webp 2048w, https://assets.editorial.aetnd.com/uploads/2009/10/japanese-internment-camps-gettyimages-1388588882.jpg?width=3840&amp;height=1920&amp;crop=3840%3A1920%2Csmart&amp;quality=75&amp;auto=webp 3840w" src="https://assets.editorial.aetnd.com/uploads/2009/10/japanese-internment-camps-gettyimages-1388588882.jpg?width=3840&amp;height=1920&amp;crop=3840%3A1920%2Csmart&amp;quality=75&amp;auto=webp" decoding="async" data-nimg="fill" style="position:absolute;top:0;left:0;bottom:0;right:0;box-sizing:border-box;padding:0;border:none;margin:auto;display:block;width:0;height:0;min-width:100%;max-width:100%;min-height:100%;max-height:100%;object-fit:cover"/></span><figcaption class="image-credit"><a target="_blank" rel="noreferrer" href="https://www.gettyimages.com/detail/news-photo/high-angle-view-of-the-huts-of-the-minidoka-war-relocation-news-photo/1388588882?phrase=Japanese%20Internment%20Camps&amp;adppopup=true">UPI/Bettmann Archive/Getty Images</a></figcaption></figure></header><div class="article-content-box"><div class="article-intro-toc"><nav class="block-table-of-contents" role="navigation" aria-labelledby="table-of-contents-heading"><h2 class="block-table-of-contents__heading" id="table-of-contents-heading">Table of Contents</h2><ol class="block-table-of-contents__list"><li class="block-table-of-contents__element button is-style-standalone"><a href="#executive-order-9066" class="block-table-of-contents__link">Executive Order 9066</a></li><li class="block-table-of-contents__element button is-style-standalone"><a href="#anti-japanese-american-activity" class="block-table-of-contents__link">Anti-Japanese American Activity&amp;nbsp;</a></li><li class="block-table-of-contents__element button is-style-standalone"><a href="#photos-of-japanese-american-relocation-and-incarceration" class="block-table-of-contents__link">Photos of Japanese American Relocation and Incarceration</a></li><li class="block-table-of-contents__element button is-style-standalone"><a href="#john-dewitt" class="block-table-of-contents__link">John DeWitt</a></li><li class="block-table-of-contents__element button is-style-standalone"><a href="#war-relocation-authority" class="block-table-of-contents__link">War Relocation Authority</a></li><li class="block-table-of-contents__element button is-style-standalone"><a href="#relocation-to-assembly-centers" class="block-table-of-contents__link">Relocation to &#x27;Assembly Centers&#x27;</a></li><li class="block-table-of-contents__element button is-style-standalone"><a href="#life-in-assembly-centers" class="block-table-of-contents__link">Life in &#x27;Assembly Centers&#x27;</a></li><li class="block-table-of-contents__element button is-style-standalone"><a href="#conditions-in-relocation-centers" class="block-table-of-contents__link">Conditions in &#x27;Relocation Centers&#x27;</a></li><li class="block-table-of-contents__element button is-style-standalone"><a href="#violence-in-prison-camps" class="block-table-of-contents__link">Violence in Prison Camps</a></li><li class="block-table-of-contents__element button is-style-standalone"><a href="#fred-korematsu" class="block-table-of-contents__link">Fred Korematsu</a></li><li class="block-table-of-contents__element button is-style-standalone"><a href="#mitsuye-endo" class="block-table-of-contents__link">Mitsuye Endo</a></li><li class="block-table-of-contents__element button is-style-standalone"><a href="#reparations" class="block-table-of-contents__link">Reparations</a></li><li class="block-table-of-contents__element button is-style-standalone"><a href="#sources" class="block-table-of-contents__link">Sources</a></li></ol></nav><div class="article-intro"><p>Japanese internment camps were established during <a href="https://www.history.com/topics/world-war-ii/world-war-ii-history">World War II</a> by President <a href="https://www.history.com/topics/us-presidents/franklin-d-roosevelt">Franklin D. Roosevelt</a> through his <a href="https://www.archives.gov/historical-docs/todays-doc/?dod-date=219">Executive Order 9066</a>. From 1942 to 1945, it was the policy of the U.S. government that people of Japanese descent, including U.S. citizens, would be incarcerated in isolated camps. Enacted in reaction to the <a href="https://www.history.com/topics/world-war-ii/pearl-harbor">Pearl Harbor</a> attacks and the ensuing war, the incarceration of Japanese Americans is considered one of the most atrocious violations of American civil rights in the 20th century.</p></div></div><div class="article-content content"><div class="video-player wp-block wp-block-history-video"><button class="video-player__close" aria-label="Close and pause the video" type="button"><svg viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" aria-hidden="true" focusable="false"><path d="M19 6.41L17.59 5 12 10.59 6.41 5 5 6.41 10.59 12 5 17.59 6.41 19 12 13.41 17.59 19 19 17.59 13.41 12 19 6.41z" fill="currentColor"></path></svg></button><div class="video-player-decoy" style="background-image:url(https://cropper.watch.aetnd.com/public-content-aetn.video.aetnd.com/video-thumbnails/AETN-History_VMS/413/863/BRAND_SF_THC_HOSF_200170_SUP_2398_20170510_01_0513883_HD.jpg)"><div class="video-player-decoy__title-wrapper"><div class="video-player-decoy__title" aria-hidden="true">Japanese-American Relocation</div></div><button type="button" class="video-player-decoy__play" aria-label="Play Japanese-American Relocation"><span class="video-player-decoy__play-icon"></span></button></div></div><h2 id="executive-order-9066">Executive Order 9066</h2><p>On February 19, 1942, shortly after the bombing of <a href="https://www.history.com/topics/world-war-ii/pearl-harbor">Pearl Harbor</a> by Japanese forces, President Roosevelt <a href="https://www.history.com/topics/executive-order">signed Executive Order 9066</a> with the stated intention of preventing espionage on American shores.</p><p>Military zones were created in California, Washington and Oregon—states with a large population of Japanese Americans. Then Roosevelt’s executive order forcibly removed Americans of Japanese ancestry from their homes. Executive Order 9066 affected the lives about 120,000 people—the majority of whom were American citizens.</p><p>Canada soon followed suit, forcibly removing 21,000 of its residents of Japanese descent from its west coast. <a href="https://www.history.com/topics/mexico">Mexico</a> enacted its own version, and eventually 2,264 more people of Japanese descent were forcibly removed from Peru, Brazil, Chile and Argentina to the United States.</p><h2 id="anti-japanese-american-activity">Anti-Japanese American Activity&nbsp;</h2><p>Weeks before the order, the Navy removed citizens of Japanese descent from Terminal Island near the Port of Los Angeles.</p><p>On December 7, 1941, just hours after the bombing of Pearl Harbor, the <a href="/topics/fbi">FBI</a> rounded-up 1,291 Japanese American community and religious leaders, arresting them without evidence and freezing their assets.</p><p>In January, the arrestees were transferred to prison camps in Montana, New Mexico and North Dakota, many unable to inform their families and most remaining for the duration of the war.</p><p>Concurrently, the FBI searched the private homes of thousands of Japanese American residents on the West Coast, seizing items considered contraband.</p><p>One-third of Hawaii’s population was of Japanese descent. In a panic, some politicians called for their mass incarceration. Japanese-owned fishing boats were impounded.</p><p>Some Japanese American residents were arrested and 1,500 people—one percent of the Japanese population in Hawaii—were sent to prison camps on the U.S. mainland.</p><h2 class="has-text-align-center" id="photos-of-japanese-american-relocation-and-incarceration">Photos of Japanese American Relocation and Incarceration</h2><div class="wp-block-gallery is-style-slideshow is-style-slideshow" id="gallery-4c18e1b8-d03a-4bfd-9e32-6356cd6398db"><div class="container"><div class="swiper"><div class="swiper-wrapper"><figure class="swiper-slide slideshow-gallery__slide"><div class="slideshow-gallery__image-wrapper"><span style="box-sizing:border-box;display:block;overflow:hidden;width:initial;height:initial;background:none;opacity:1;border:0;margin:0;padding:0;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;bottom:0;right:0"><img alt="" src="data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAAAAAAP///yH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAIBRAA7" decoding="async" data-nimg="fill" style="position:absolute;top:0;left:0;bottom:0;right:0;box-sizing:border-box;padding:0;border:none;margin:auto;display:block;width:0;height:0;min-width:100%;max-width:100%;min-height:100%;max-height:100%;object-fit:contain;object-position:center center"/><noscript><img alt="" sizes="(min-width: 636px) 704px, 100vw" srcSet="https://assets.editorial.aetnd.com/uploads/2009/10/japanese_internment_camps_getty-514877912.jpg?width=640&amp;amp%3Bheight=400&amp;amp%3Bcrop=2%3A1&amp;quality=75&amp;auto=webp 640w, https://assets.editorial.aetnd.com/uploads/2009/10/japanese_internment_camps_getty-514877912.jpg?width=750&amp;amp%3Bheight=400&amp;amp%3Bcrop=2%3A1&amp;quality=75&amp;auto=webp 750w, https://assets.editorial.aetnd.com/uploads/2009/10/japanese_internment_camps_getty-514877912.jpg?width=828&amp;amp%3Bheight=400&amp;amp%3Bcrop=2%3A1&amp;quality=75&amp;auto=webp 828w, https://assets.editorial.aetnd.com/uploads/2009/10/japanese_internment_camps_getty-514877912.jpg?width=1080&amp;amp%3Bheight=400&amp;amp%3Bcrop=2%3A1&amp;quality=75&amp;auto=webp 1080w, https://assets.editorial.aetnd.com/uploads/2009/10/japanese_internment_camps_getty-514877912.jpg?width=1248&amp;amp%3Bheight=400&amp;amp%3Bcrop=2%3A1&amp;quality=75&amp;auto=webp 1248w, https://assets.editorial.aetnd.com/uploads/2009/10/japanese_internment_camps_getty-514877912.jpg?width=1920&amp;amp%3Bheight=400&amp;amp%3Bcrop=2%3A1&amp;quality=75&amp;auto=webp 1920w, https://assets.editorial.aetnd.com/uploads/2009/10/japanese_internment_camps_getty-514877912.jpg?width=2048&amp;amp%3Bheight=400&amp;amp%3Bcrop=2%3A1&amp;quality=75&amp;auto=webp 2048w, https://assets.editorial.aetnd.com/uploads/2009/10/japanese_internment_camps_getty-514877912.jpg?width=3840&amp;amp%3Bheight=400&amp;amp%3Bcrop=2%3A1&amp;quality=75&amp;auto=webp 3840w" src="https://assets.editorial.aetnd.com/uploads/2009/10/japanese_internment_camps_getty-514877912.jpg?width=3840&amp;amp%3Bheight=400&amp;amp%3Bcrop=2%3A1&amp;quality=75&amp;auto=webp" decoding="async" data-nimg="fill" style="position:absolute;top:0;left:0;bottom:0;right:0;box-sizing:border-box;padding:0;border:none;margin:auto;display:block;width:0;height:0;min-width:100%;max-width:100%;min-height:100%;max-height:100%;object-fit:contain;object-position:center center" loading="lazy"/></noscript></span></div><figcaption class="slideshow-gallery__caption">President Franklin D. Roosevelt signed&nbsp;Executive Order 9066&nbsp;in February 1942&nbsp;calling for the internment of Japanese-Americans after the attacks on Pearl Harbor.&nbsp;The Mochida family, pictured here, were some of the&nbsp;117,000 people that would be forced into prison camps scattered throughout the country by that June.</figcaption></figure><figure class="swiper-slide slideshow-gallery__slide"><div class="slideshow-gallery__image-wrapper"><span style="box-sizing:border-box;display:block;overflow:hidden;width:initial;height:initial;background:none;opacity:1;border:0;margin:0;padding:0;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;bottom:0;right:0"><img alt="" src="data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAAAAAAP///yH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAIBRAA7" decoding="async" data-nimg="fill" style="position:absolute;top:0;left:0;bottom:0;right:0;box-sizing:border-box;padding:0;border:none;margin:auto;display:block;width:0;height:0;min-width:100%;max-width:100%;min-height:100%;max-height:100%;object-fit:contain;object-position:center center"/><noscript><img alt="" sizes="(min-width: 636px) 704px, 100vw" srcSet="https://assets.editorial.aetnd.com/uploads/2009/10/japanese_internment_camps_getty-615309184.jpg?width=640&amp;amp%3Bheight=400&amp;amp%3Bcrop=2%3A1&amp;quality=75&amp;auto=webp 640w, https://assets.editorial.aetnd.com/uploads/2009/10/japanese_internment_camps_getty-615309184.jpg?width=750&amp;amp%3Bheight=400&amp;amp%3Bcrop=2%3A1&amp;quality=75&amp;auto=webp 750w, https://assets.editorial.aetnd.com/uploads/2009/10/japanese_internment_camps_getty-615309184.jpg?width=828&amp;amp%3Bheight=400&amp;amp%3Bcrop=2%3A1&amp;quality=75&amp;auto=webp 828w, https://assets.editorial.aetnd.com/uploads/2009/10/japanese_internment_camps_getty-615309184.jpg?width=1080&amp;amp%3Bheight=400&amp;amp%3Bcrop=2%3A1&amp;quality=75&amp;auto=webp 1080w, https://assets.editorial.aetnd.com/uploads/2009/10/japanese_internment_camps_getty-615309184.jpg?width=1248&amp;amp%3Bheight=400&amp;amp%3Bcrop=2%3A1&amp;quality=75&amp;auto=webp 1248w, https://assets.editorial.aetnd.com/uploads/2009/10/japanese_internment_camps_getty-615309184.jpg?width=1920&amp;amp%3Bheight=400&amp;amp%3Bcrop=2%3A1&amp;quality=75&amp;auto=webp 1920w, https://assets.editorial.aetnd.com/uploads/2009/10/japanese_internment_camps_getty-615309184.jpg?width=2048&amp;amp%3Bheight=400&amp;amp%3Bcrop=2%3A1&amp;quality=75&amp;auto=webp 2048w, https://assets.editorial.aetnd.com/uploads/2009/10/japanese_internment_camps_getty-615309184.jpg?width=3840&amp;amp%3Bheight=400&amp;amp%3Bcrop=2%3A1&amp;quality=75&amp;auto=webp 3840w" src="https://assets.editorial.aetnd.com/uploads/2009/10/japanese_internment_camps_getty-615309184.jpg?width=3840&amp;amp%3Bheight=400&amp;amp%3Bcrop=2%3A1&amp;quality=75&amp;auto=webp" decoding="async" data-nimg="fill" style="position:absolute;top:0;left:0;bottom:0;right:0;box-sizing:border-box;padding:0;border:none;margin:auto;display:block;width:0;height:0;min-width:100%;max-width:100%;min-height:100%;max-height:100%;object-fit:contain;object-position:center center" loading="lazy"/></noscript></span></div><figcaption class="slideshow-gallery__caption">This Oakland, California grocery was owned by a Japanese-American and graduate of the University of California. The day after the Pearl Harbor attacks he put up his 'I Am An American' sign to prove his patriotism. Soon afterward, the government shut down the shop and forced the owner to a prison camp.&nbsp;</figcaption></figure><figure class="swiper-slide slideshow-gallery__slide"><div class="slideshow-gallery__image-wrapper"><span style="box-sizing:border-box;display:block;overflow:hidden;width:initial;height:initial;background:none;opacity:1;border:0;margin:0;padding:0;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;bottom:0;right:0"><img alt="" src="data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAAAAAAP///yH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAA