cate to a Japanese prison camp. His case made it all the way to the Supreme Court, where his attorneys argued in \u003ca href=\"https://www.uscourts.gov/educational-resources/educational-activities/facts-and-case-summary-korematsu-v-us\"\u003eKorematsu v. United States\u003c/a\u003e that Executive Order 9066 violated the \u003ca href=\"https://www.history.com/topics/united-states-constitution/bill-of-rights\"\u003eFifth Amendment\u003c/a\u003e.\u0026nbsp;","dropCap":false},"innerBlocks":[]},{"clientId":"b9506001-fcad-43cd-a180-e48f9e73abb7","name":"core/paragraph","attributes":{"content":"Korematsu lost the case, but he went on to become a civil rights activist and was awarded the Presidential Medal of Freedom in 1998. With the creation of California’s Fred Korematsu Day, the United States saw its first U.S. holiday named for an Asian American. But it took another Supreme Court decision to halt the incarceration of Japanese Americans. ","dropCap":false},"innerBlocks":[]},{"clientId":"c7a01f40-3fdf-4f84-b44e-087c342123b8","name":"core/heading","attributes":{"content":"Mitsuye Endo","level":2,"id":"mitsuye-endo"},"innerBlocks":[]},{"clientId":"a00e18f3-b758-4e72-a87a-ae51ca7d1c9a","name":"core/paragraph","attributes":{"content":"The prison camps ended in 1945 following the\u0026nbsp;\u003ca href=\"/topics/supreme-court-facts\"\u003eSupreme Court\u003c/a\u003e decision,\u0026nbsp;\u003cem\u003e\u003ca href=\"https://www.loc.gov/item/usrep323283/\"\u003eEx parte Mitsuye Endo\u003c/a\u003e\u003c/em\u003e.\u0026nbsp;In this case, justices ruled unanimously that the War Relocation Authority “has no authority to subject citizens who are concededly loyal to its leave procedure.”","dropCap":false},"innerBlocks":[]},{"clientId":"174318d7-e271-4663-aba8-573ad232a62b","name":"core/paragraph","attributes":{"content":"The case was brought on behalf of Mitsuye Endo, the daughter of Japanese immigrants from Sacramento, California. After filing a habeas corpus petition, the government offered to free her, but Endo refused, wanting her case to address the entire issue of Japanese incarceration.","dropCap":false},"innerBlocks":[]},{"clientId":"128b0b6b-e0df-4ea5-b4bd-226468b38f5c","name":"core/paragraph","attributes":{"content":"One year later, the Supreme Court made the decision, but gave President Truman the chance to begin camp closures before the announcement. One day after Truman made his announcement, the Supreme Court revealed its decision.","dropCap":false},"innerBlocks":[]},{"clientId":"8a5afc1e-20f1-4bb7-a9ef-37afca11a5fc","name":"core/heading","attributes":{"content":"Reparations","level":2,"id":"reparations"},"innerBlocks":[]},{"clientId":"32f2b725-380f-468b-9c50-2dabf34a9e25","name":"core/paragraph","attributes":{"content":"The last Japanese internment camp closed in March 1946. President \u003ca href=\"https://www.history.com/topics/us-presidents/gerald-r-ford\"\u003eGerald Ford\u003c/a\u003e officially repealed Executive Order 9066 in 1976, and in 1988, Congress issued a formal apology and passed the Civil Liberties Act awarding $20,000 each to over 80,000 Japanese Americans as \u003ca href=\"https://www.history.com/news/reparations-slavery-native-americans-japanese-internment\"\u003ereparations\u003c/a\u003e for their treatment.","dropCap":false},"innerBlocks":[]},{"clientId":"b211b926-ed53-420d-8731-024c296c1a8d","name":"core/heading","attributes":{"content":"Sources","level":2,"id":"sources"},"innerBlocks":[]},{"clientId":"8583c2b1-189a-4fb4-b57b-922803b5c1ec","name":"core/paragraph","attributes":{"content":"Japanese Relocation During \u003ca href=\"/topics/world-war-ii\"\u003eWorld War II\u003c/a\u003e. \u003ca href=\"https://www.archives.gov/education/lessons/japanese-relocation\"\u003eNational Archives\u003c/a\u003e.\u003cbr /\u003eConfinement and Ethnicity: An Overview of World War II Japanese American Relocation Sites. \u003ca href=\"https://www.nps.gov/articles/historyinternment.htm\"\u003eJ. Burton, M. Farrell, F. Lord and R. Lord\u003c/a\u003e.\u003cbr /\u003eLordsburg Internment POW Camp. \u003ca href=\"http://newmexicohistory.org/places/lordsburg-internment-pow-camp\"\u003eHistorical Society of New Mexico\u003c/a\u003e.\u003cbr /\u003e\u003ca href=\"http://amhistory.si.edu/perfectunion/non-flash/internment_main.html\"\u003eSmithsonian Institute\u003c/a\u003e.","dropCap":false},"innerBlocks":[]},{"clientId":"babe04e4-b950-42c9-b8c5-ab24269a8b56","name":"core/columns","attributes":{"isStackedOnMobile":true},"innerBlocks":[{"clientId":"8ab52d85-a526-492e-8c40-b8d241a19fea","name":"core/column","attributes":{"verticalAlignment":"center","width":"33.33%"},"innerBlocks":[{"clientId":"c7cb0b14-a3ef-48e9-8fc9-5af6e731b9b4","name":"core/image","attributes":{"id":47487,"sizeSlug":"large","linkDestination":"none","url":"https://assets.editorial.aetnd.com/uploads/2021/04/FDR_3840x2160.jpg?width=1024\u0026amp;height=576","alt":"","width":1024,"height":576},"innerBlocks":[]}]},{"clientId":"8e970e36-4008-4fde-be3d-b61e8b2a8e54","name":"core/column","attributes":{"verticalAlignment":"center","width":"66.66%"},"innerBlocks":[{"clientId":"95d19ea7-4bb0-408c-9429-df6c87728bb0","name":"core/heading","attributes":{"level":3,"fontSize":"heading-4","content":"FDR"},"innerBlocks":[]},{"clientId":"b61d6057-f2b6-4554-99d5-a564911266e2","name":"core/paragraph","attributes":{"content":"Watch the documentary event, \u003cstrong\u003eFDR\u003c/strong\u003e. Available to stream now.","dropCap":false},"innerBlocks":[]},{"clientId":"44f58191-ce0e-4c8c-98a0-86ec240bff55","name":"core/buttons","attributes":[],"innerBlocks":[{"clientId":"cb707079-e9d3-4db3-b914-97d615c14461","name":"core/button","attributes":{"tagName":"a","type":"button","url":"play.history.com/shows/fdr","text":"watch now","linkTarget":"_blank","rel":"noreferrer noopener"},"innerBlocks":[]}]}]}]}]},"excerpt":{"rendered":"Executive Order 9066 On February 19, 1942, shortly after the bombing of Pearl Harbor by Japanese forces, President Roosevelt si