ast. \u003ca href=\"https://www.history.com/topics/mexico\"\u003eMexico\u003c/a\u003e enacted its own version, and eventually 2,264 more people of Japanese descent were forcibly removed from Peru, Brazil, Chile and Argentina to the United States.","dropCap":false},"innerBlocks":[]},{"clientId":"aaff8ab8-13e7-454f-a7e7-ad620684095d","name":"core/heading","attributes":{"content":"Anti-Japanese American Activity\u0026nbsp;","level":2,"id":"anti-japanese-american-activity"},"innerBlocks":[]},{"clientId":"fda3c6aa-d168-48e9-a2f6-d215d9dd03ab","name":"core/paragraph","attributes":{"content":"Weeks before the order, the Navy removed citizens of Japanese descent from Terminal Island near the Port of Los Angeles.","dropCap":false},"innerBlocks":[]},{"clientId":"a9c0322a-7792-4ae5-82d3-f62e23a920c9","name":"core/paragraph","attributes":{"content":"On December 7, 1941, just hours after the bombing of Pearl Harbor, the \u003ca href=\"/topics/fbi\"\u003eFBI\u003c/a\u003e rounded-up 1,291 Japanese American community and religious leaders, arresting them without evidence and freezing their assets.","dropCap":false},"innerBlocks":[]},{"clientId":"6bfb04d4-29ee-4c02-b755-56f8984e0ce3","name":"core/paragraph","attributes":{"content":"In January, the arrestees were transferred to prison camps in Montana, New Mexico and North Dakota, many unable to inform their families and most remaining for the duration of the war.","dropCap":false},"innerBlocks":[]},{"clientId":"ba4c00b3-6f84-4df7-8313-1ee11b7c0a9b","name":"core/paragraph","attributes":{"content":"Concurrently, the FBI searched the private homes of thousands of Japanese American residents on the West Coast, seizing items considered contraband.","dropCap":false},"innerBlocks":[]},{"clientId":"0ed2ffe9-cdc5-42eb-beb7-e33767a01455","name":"core/paragraph","attributes":{"content":"One-third of Hawaii’s population was of Japanese descent. In a panic, some politicians called for their mass incarceration. Japanese-owned fishing boats were 