atsu-japanese-internment-supreme-court\",\"title\":\"Korematsu Ruling on Japanese Internment: Condemned But Not Overruled\",\"type\":\"story\"},{\"id\":40447,\"link\":\"https://www.history.com/news/442nd-regiment-combat-japanese-american-wwii-internment-camps\",\"title\":\"How Two Japanese Americans Fought Nazis Abroad—and Prejudice at Home\",\"type\":\"story\"},{\"id\":28415,\"link\":\"https://www.history.com/news/japanese-american-wwii-incarceration-camps-redress\",\"title\":\"How Japanese Americans Fought for—and Won—Redress for WWII Incarceration\",\"type\":\"story\"}]","className":"is-style-3-col","preview":false},"innerBlocks":[]},{"clientId":"6585c35c-289b-4da8-98c3-26db0690e380","name":"core/heading","attributes":{"content":"Fred Korematsu","level":2,"id":"fred-korematsu"},"innerBlocks":[]},{"clientId":"e149d51c-efdd-4905-a88d-b7facfc616a1","name":"core/paragraph","attributes":{"content":" In 1942, 23-year-old\u0026nbsp;Japanese-American Fred Korematsu was arrested for refusing to relocate to a Japanese prison camp. His case made it all the way to the Supreme Court, where his attorneys argued in \u003ca href=\"https://www.uscourts.gov/educational-resources/educational-activities/facts-and-case-summary-korematsu-v-us\"\u003eKorematsu v. United States\u003c/a\u003e that Executive Order 9066 violated the \u003ca href=\"https://www.history.com/topics/united-states-constitution/bill-of-rights\"\u003eFifth Amendment\u003c/a\u003e.\u0026nbsp;","dropCap":false},"innerBlocks":[]},{"clientId":"b9506001-fcad-43cd-a180-e48f9e73abb7","name":"core/paragraph","attributes":{"content":"Korematsu lost the case, but he went on to become a civil rights activist and was awarded the Presidential Medal of Freedom in 1998. With the creation of California’s Fred Korematsu Day, the United States saw its first U.S. holiday named for an Asian American. But it took another Supreme Court decision to halt the incarceration of Japanese Americans. ","dropCap":false},"innerBlocks":[]},{"clie